ef="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a></a></a> been missing is a metaphorical play that can be included in all postseason video packages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That changed on Friday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>[<a href="https://bs.serving-sys.com/BurstingPipe/adServer.bs?cn=tf&amp;c=20&amp;mc=click&amp;pli=13662960&amp;PluID=0%E2%A9%9D=%24%7BCACHEBUSTER%7D">Play a Daily Fantasy contest for cash today!</a>]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an 8-2 loss to the last-place <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/teams/phi/">Philadelphia Phillies</a>, center fielder <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/ncaaf/players/257089/">Michael Taylor</a> did his own version of the crash and burn, playing an <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/players/9734/">Aaron Altherr</a> basehit into a game-changing, inside-the-park grand slam that will effectively crush the Nationals faint postseason hopes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The unfortunate play happened in the third inning. With one out, Altherr hit a sinking line drive to short center field that Taylor obviously thought he had a chance to catch. He was mistaken, and that mistake proved very costly as the ball skipped past him and rolled nearly to the warning track. That allowed all three baserunners, as well as Altherr, who raced around with MLB&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a></a></a> first inside-the-park grand slam since 1999.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="https://twitter.com/MLBONFOX/status/647557754073157632">According to FOX Sports on Twitter,</a> the last one belonged to Randy Winn then of the <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/teams/nyy/">New York Yankees</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two innings later, Altherr would continue his big night with a solo home run. That time, he went back-to-back with Darren Ruf. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Needless to say, this wasn&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;t">#39;t</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;t">#39;t</a></a> a memorable night for <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/players/8400/">Jordan Zimmermann</a>. The impending free agent was making what could prove to be his final home start for the Nationals, but could last only five innings, allowing the six runs already noted of those three home runs. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was the type of game that has killed the Nationals all season. On paper, it looked like a mismatch in their favor. They just didn&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;t">#39;t</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;t">#39;t</a></a> play anything resembling good enough baseball to win, and now they enter play on Saturday knowing one more loss or one more Mets win spells the end of their postseason chances.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Aaron Altherr crushes Nationals with inside-the-park grand slam', 0, 0, NULL, 5, 2, 0),
(38, 3, '2015-09-26', '04:40:00', '<p><a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/teams/pit/">Pittsburgh Pirates</a> outfielder <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/players/7977/">Andrew McCutchen</a> won&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>t"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>t</a> be singing any lines from &<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>Sweet"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>Sweet</a> Home Chicago&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a> this weekend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, unless he decides to change the words.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>[<a href="https://bs.serving-sys.com/BurstingPipe/adServer.bs?cn=tf&amp;c=20&amp;mc=click&amp;pli=13662960&amp;PluID=0%E2%A9%9D=%24%7BCACHEBUSTER%7D">Play a Daily Fantasy contest for cash today!</a>]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the former National League MVP arrived to the Windy City late Thursday night for his club&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s important weekend series at Wrigley Field, he found his hotel room to be anything but sweet, homely or accommodating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was more, well, take a look for yourself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s an MVP supposed to get any sleep around here?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unkempt is that word we&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>re looking for. Of course, we&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>re sure this was a simple oversight from the hotel&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s housekeeping staff. Stuff like that will happen from time to time, and this time it just so happened to be one of the most important players in MLB. Who also has a highly followed Twitter and Instragram we might add. Such an unfortunate coincidence. Or was it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>re 98.2 percent certain the Cubs were just having a little fun with that tweet. Or maybe 98.2 percent was the Cubs playoff chances entering play Friday. It&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s so difficult keeping track of this stuff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Either way, it wouldn&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>t"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>t</a> have much impact on Friday&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s game. Though McCutchen was held in check, going 0-for-4 with two strikeouts, the Pirates went on to win the game 3-2. That extended their wild card lead over Chicago to 4 1/2 games, while denying the Cubs a chance to clinch a playoff berth in front of the home fans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The obvious Pirates response there being, if Chicago won&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>t"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>t</a> make our beds, we&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>re going to be really terrible guests. Or something along those lines. We might be overthinking that, but it&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s September and that&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;">#39;</a>s when things really start to get crazy. Anything is possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Chicago hospitality: Andrew McCutchen arrives to unkempt hotel room', 0, 0, NULL, 2, 2, 0),
(39, 3, '2015-09-26', '04:41:49', '<p>If you&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a></a></a> wondering what Bobby Valentine, the ex-New York Mets and <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/teams/tex/">Texas Rangers</a> manager, has been up to lately. Well, apparently, he&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a></a> been pondering the future of performance enhancing drugs in sports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are the things, apparently, you spend your time doing after you&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;ve">#39;ve</a> supposedly <a href="http://www.thepostgame.com/blog/dish/201112/new-red-sox-manager-bobby-valentines-odd-food-invention">invented the wrap sandwich</a> and served as <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/big-league-stew/bye-bye-bobby-valentine-gets-axed-red-sox-174952885--mlb.html">a one-year punchline manager</a> with the <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/teams/bos/">Boston Red Sox</a>. Anyhow, our old buddy Bobby V. sat down with Maggie Gray for an installment of <a href="http://www.si.com/mlb/2015/09/25/bobby-valentine-peds-steroids-drugs-sports">Sports Illustrated Now</a> in which he talks about all the merits of PEDs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[<strong>Elsewhere</strong>: <strong><a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/mlb-big-league-stew/madison-bumgarner-gets-into-an-intense-staredown-with-umpire-joe-west-192205820.html">Madison Bumgarner gets into intense staredown with ump Joe West</a></strong>]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The segment &mdash; which you can <a href="http://www.si.com/mlb/2015/09/25/bobby-valentine-peds-steroids-drugs-sports">watch here</a> &mdash;&nbsp;starts with Gray asking Valentine if he thinks PEDs will be legal and whether that&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a></a> a good thing for sports.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Probably, if you want to see the best out of your athlete,&rdquo; Valentine said. &quot;If it&rsquo;s not harmful to the athlete.&quot;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p>This, of course, flies in the face of all PED objector logic that says &quot;cheating&quot; is wrong and we want our athletes to play the game clean. Valentine then compares PEDs to weight rooms &mdash; in that they started out as a thing baseball teams were against using, but now everybody has &<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;em.">#39;em.</a> Anybody else look like <a href="http://www.theawl.com/2014/05/the-life-and-times-of-%C2%AF_%E3%83%84_%C2%AF">a shrug emoticon</a> right now or just us? Is that really the best comparison?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Later Valentine &mdash; who we probably should add is the&nbsp;director of athletics at <a href="http://sacredheartpioneers.com/information/directory/index">Sacred Heart University</a> in Connecticut&nbsp;&mdash; would go on to say:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>&quot;There&rsquo;s a lot of really good drugs out there that we do take that make us feel better and perform better, and I think these PEDs that people talk about, that are performance-enhancers, will eventually get into the mainstream.&rdquo;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>[<a href="https://bs.serving-sys.com/BurstingPipe/adServer.bs?cn=tf&amp;c=20&amp;mc=click&amp;pli=13662960&amp;PluID=0%E2%A9%9D=%24%7BCACHEBUSTER%7D">Play a Daily Fantasy contest for cash today!</a>]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maybe he&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;s">#39;s</a></a></a> talking about a distant future in which our robot overlords have rid the world of harmful drugs and all steroids or hormones we inject into our body have good consequences. Maybe. And maybe in that future, pizza is healthy, Cyborg Jeffrey Loria is the most beloved owner in baseball and Kanye West is Pope or something.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But if we&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a></a></a> talking about a near future in which baseball &mdash; or any other sport &mdash; tells its athletes &quot;Eh, just take whatever you want,&quot; we&<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a></a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=<a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a>"><a href="searchtags.php?tag=#39;re">#39;re</a></a></a> going to have to disagree with Valentine that such a day is coming. Drug rules may change over time, sure. But PED&nbsp;anarchy is not on the horizon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Bobby Valentine thinks PEDs are good for sports, will eventually be legal', 0, 0, NULL, 0, 2, 0);
