(49, 3, '2015-09-26', '05:09:35', '<p>A <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/08/opinion/the-anti-party-men-trump-carson-sanders-and-corbyn.html">lot</a> of <a href="http://www.nationalreview.com/article/422716/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-populism">people</a> are <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/09/07/the-populists">linking</a> the candidacies of Bernie Sanders and Donald Trump under headings like &ldquo;populist&rdquo; and &ldquo;anti-establishment.&rdquo; Most of these comparisons are too cute for their own good &mdash; not only because it&rsquo;s <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/keep-calm-and-ignore-the-2016-game-changers/">too early</a> to come to many conclusions about the campaign, but also because Trump and Sanders are fundamentally different breeds of candidates who are situated very differently in their respective nomination races.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can call both &ldquo;outsiders.&rdquo; But if you&rsquo;re a Democrat, Sanders is your eccentric uncle: He has his own quirks, but he&rsquo;s part of the family. If you&rsquo;re a Republican, Trump is as familial as the vacuum salesman knocking on your door.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Consider the following. We&rsquo;ll start with some of the more superficial differences between Sanders and Trump and work our way to the more important ones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1. Trump is &ldquo;winning&rdquo; (for now), and Sanders isn&rsquo;t. </strong>There are <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/donald-trumps-six-stages-of-doom/">lots of reasons</a> to suspect that Trump will fall from his position atop the GOP polls sooner or later, but he&rsquo;d be a favorite to win a hypothetical national primary held today. Sanders, by contrast, <a href="http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2016/president/us/2016_democratic_presidential_nomination-3824.html">trails Hillary Clinton</a> by about 20 percentage points in national polls that include Joe Biden, and by 30 points in polls that don&rsquo;t.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. Sanders is campaigning on substantive policy positions, and Trump is largely campaigning on the force of his personality. </strong>I&rsquo;m not sure this assertion requires a lot of proof, but if you need some, check out the candidates&rsquo; websites. Sanders&rsquo;s lists <a href="https://berniesanders.com/issues/">dozens of specific policy proposals</a> across a wide range of issues; Trump&rsquo;s <a href="https://www.donaldjtrump.com/positions">details his position on just one</a>, immigration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Screen Shot 2015-09-08 at 8.55.00 PM" src="https://espnfivethirtyeight.files.wordpress.com/2015/09/screen-shot-2015-09-08-at-8-55-00-pm.png?w=610&amp;h=364" style="height:364px; width:610px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. Sanders is a career politician; Trump isn&rsquo;t. </strong>Let&rsquo;s not neglect this obvious one. Bernie Sanders has been in Congress since 1991, making him one of the <a href="http://www.rollcall.com/politics/houseseniority.html">most senior members of Congress</a>; Trump has never officially run a political campaign before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>4. Trump is getting considerably more media attention. </strong>Trump is a <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/donald-trump-is-running-a-perpetual-attention-machine/">perpetual attention machine</a> who gets a disproportionate amount of media coverage &mdash; as much as the rest of the GOP field combined. Sanders hasn&rsquo;t been ignored by the press, <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/hillary-clinton-scandal-inevitable-problems/">which wants a horse race</a> between Sanders (or Biden, or anyone!!!) and Clinton. Still, Sanders&rsquo;s media coverage has been paltry compared with Trump&rsquo;s. According to <a href="https://news.search.yahoo.com/search?p=donald+trump&amp;fr=uh3_news_web_gs&amp;fr2=p%3Anews%2Cm%3Asb">Yahoo News</a>, Trump has received about 35,000 media &ldquo;hits&rdquo; in the past month, compared with about 9,000 for Sanders. For comparison, Clinton has had 18,000 hits over the same period, and Jeb Bush has had 14,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2016-endorsement-primary/"><img alt="Candidate Approvals" src="https://espnfivethirtyeight.files.wordpress.com/2015/07/candidate_approvals_grey1-15.png?quality=100&amp;strip=all&amp;w=153&amp;h=115" style="height:115px; width:153px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>INTERACTIVE:</strong> We&rsquo;re tracking 2016 presidential primary endorsements. <a href="http://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2016-endorsement-primary/">Check out the most important race before the actual race &raquo;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>5. Sanders has a much better &ldquo;ground game.&rdquo; </strong>Trump, in addition to his ubiquity on television, has <a href="http://www.p2016.org/trump/trumporg.html">some semblance of a campaign operation</a>. But Sanders&rsquo;s organization is <a href="http://www.p2016.org/sanders/sandersorg.html">much larger and more experienced</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>6. Sanders holds policy positions of a typical liberal Democrat; Trump&rsquo;s are all over the place. </strong>While Sanders <a href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/08/bernie-sanders-2016-democrats-121181">doesn&rsquo;t officially call himself a Democrat</a> &mdash; a fact that might annoy Democratic elites &mdash; he takes policy positions that are consistent with those of Democrats in Congress. In the previous Congress (113th), Sanders voted the same as liberal Democratic senators Barbara Boxer, Cory Booker, Kirsten Gillibrand and Sherrod Brown 95 percent of the time or more.<a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/stop-comparing-donald-trump-and-bernie-sanders/#fn-1">1</a> He voted with party leader Harry Reid 91 percent of the time and the expressed position of President Obama<a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/stop-comparing-donald-trump-and-bernie-sanders/#fn-2">2</a> 93 percent of the time. He also <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/28/upshot/the-senate-votes-that-divided-hillary-clinton-and-bernie-sanders.html">voted with Clinton 93 percent of the time</a> when the two were in the Senate together.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are the senators Sanders voted with most and least often in the 113th Congress, according to <a href="http://www.voteview.com/">Voteview.org</a>:</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th colspan="1">SENATOR</th>\r\n			<th colspan="1">MOST OFTEN</th>\r\n			<th colspan="1">SENATOR</th>\r\n			<th colspan="1">LEAST OFTEN</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Boxer (CA)</td>\r\n			<td>96.2%</td>\r\n			<td>Manchin (WV)</td>\r\n			<td>82.1%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Markey (MA)</td>\r\n			<td>95.9</td>\r\n			<td>Baucus (MT)</td>\r\n			<td>87.4</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Booker (NJ)</td>\r\n			<td>95.8</td>\r\n			<td>Pryor (AR)</td>\r\n			<td>87.6</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Cantwell (WA)</td>\r\n			<td>95.8</td>\r\n			<td>Donnelly (IN)</td>\r\n			<td>89.9</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Leahy (VT)</td>\r\n			<td>95.7</td>\r\n			<td>Hagan (NC)</td>\r\n			<td>90.0</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Gillibrand (NY)</td>\r\n			<td>95.7</td>\r\n			<td>Heitkamp (ND)</td>\r\n			<td>90.2</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Brown (OH)</td>\r\n			<td>95.7</td>\r\n			<td>Lautenberg (NJ)</td>\r\n			<td>90.6</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Hirono (HI)</td>\r\n			<td>95.4</td>\r\n			<td>Tester (MT)</td>\r\n			<td>90.6</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Menendez (NJ)</td>\r\n			<td>95.4</td>\r\n			<td>Landrieu (LA)</td>\r\n			<td>90.6</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>Stabenow (MI)</td>\r\n			<td>95.4</td>\r\n			<td>Reid (NV)</td>\r\n			<td>91.4</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump&rsquo;s positions are harder to pin down &mdash; and he doesn&rsquo;t have a voting record to evaluate &mdash; but he has far more profound potential differences with the Republican orthodoxy on major issues ranging from taxation to health care to reproductive rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>7. Sanders&rsquo;s support divides fairly clearly along ideological and demographic lines; Trump&rsquo;s doesn&rsquo;t. </strong>So far, Sanders <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/bernie-sanders-could-win-iowa-and-new-hampshire-then-lose-everywhere-else/">has won a lot of support from white liberals</a> &mdash; which helps him in Iowa and New Hampshire &mdash; but not so much from white moderates or non-white Democrats. Each of these groups represents about a third of the Democratic primary electorate nationally, so this makes Sanders&rsquo;s <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/this-is-how-bernie-sanders-could-win/">path to the Democratic nomination</a> fairly easily to analyze; he&rsquo;ll be viable only to the extent that he gains support among the other two groups.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump&rsquo;s support, by contrast, is fairly <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/23/us/politics/why-donald-trump-wont-fold-polls-and-people-speak.html">evenly spread across a range of demographic and ideological groups</a> that appear in Republican polls. He doesn&rsquo;t do especially well (or especially poorly) with &ldquo;tea party&rdquo; voters, for instance. There are a variety of ways to interpret this &mdash; perhaps, even, the &ldquo;<a href="http://www.nationalreview.com/article/423607/donald-trump-conservative-movement-jonah-goldberg">Trumpen proletariat</a>&rdquo; is a group all its own.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>8. Sanders&rsquo;s candidacy has clear historical precedents; they&rsquo;re less obvious for Trump. </strong>Even the most formidable-seeming front-runners haven&rsquo;t won their nominations without some semblance of a fight. Clinton&rsquo;s position relative to Sanders is <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/in-sanders-vs-clinton-new-hampshire-replays-past-splits/2015/09/07/072ac4ec-5581-11e5-b8c9-944725fcd3b9_story.html">analogous</a> to the one Al Gore held against Bill Bradley in the 2000 Democratic primary. Sanders&rsquo;s campaign also has parallels to liberal stalwarts from Howard Dean to Eugene McCarthy; these candidates can have an impact on the race, but they <em>usually</em> don&rsquo;t win the nomination.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump has some commonalities also: to &ldquo;bandwagon&rdquo; candidates like Newt Gingrich and Herman Cain; to media-savvy, factional candidates like Pat Buchanan; and to self-funded candidates like Steve Forbes. None of those candidates, however, was as <a href="http://blogs.reuters.com/great-debate/2015/08/06/why-donald-trumps-hostile-takeover-bid-for-the-republican-party-is-a-loser/">openly hostile to their party</a> as Trump is with Republicans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>9. Trump is running against a field of 16 candidates; Sanders is running against one overwhelming front-runner. </strong>Trump is also in new territory in another respect. There&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2015/01/29/what_if_no_one_wins_the_gop_presidential_nomination_125426.html">never been a Republican nomination race</a> &mdash; or for that matter a Democratic one &mdash; with so many declared candidates. Most of the Republicans are not tokenish candidates either. All but Trump, Ben Carson and Carly Fiorina have served as senators or governors before, many of them in highly populous states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This unprecedented volume of candidates helps Trump in various ways. For instance, it <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/donald-trump-is-the-nickelback-of-gop-candidates/">increases the value of differentiating yourself from the field</a>. Unorthodox or even unpopular policy positions may <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/donald-trump-is-winning-the-polls-and-losing-the-nomination/">help you win a faction of the Republican electorate</a>, even if it makes you less popular within your party overall. That faction may be enough to carry the plurality in polls, leading to favorable media coverage and then creating a virtuous cycle that attracts some <a href="http://researchdmr.com/Why_Are_Polls_Self_Fulfilling_Prophecies">bandwagon voters</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the abundance of candidates seems to have resulted in the Republican establishment <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/the-republican-establishment-is-waiting-on-the-sidelines/">holding off on throwing its support to any one candidate</a>, either through <a href="http://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2016-endorsement-primary/">endorsements</a> or <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/19/us/seeing-crowd-gop-donors-holding-back.html">in the money race</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Democratic establishment, by contrast, has <a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/republicans-are-acting-like-democrats-democrats-are-acting-like-republicans/">never been so united</a> behind any non-incumbent candidate as they are with Clinton.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Stop Comparing Donald Trump And Bernie Sanders', 0, 0, NULL, 0, 6, 0),
(50, 3, '2015-09-26', '05:11:54', '<p>Moldy New Orleans still lay in ruins in January of 2006 as Joe Canizaro drove me to a favorite Italian restaurant of his in the city&rsquo;s suburbs. It was a balmy Sunday, just four months after the catastrophic collapse of the city&rsquo;s flood protection system, and Canizaro asked me a question I&rsquo;ve never been able to answer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Gary, what would you do?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Canizaro &mdash; a big-name real estate developer in town &mdash; was due to deliver an official plan for redeveloping New Orleans the next day. But he confessed that he was still struggling with it. The question he asked was simple but profound: Should the authorities rebuild all of New Orleans after the flood? Or should they &ldquo;shrink the footprint&rdquo; and declare the lowest-lying areas of the city off-limits, converting large tracts of land into green space?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &ldquo;<a href="http://www.nola.com/katrina/index.ssf/2015/05/footprint_gentrification_katri.html">Great Katrina Footprint Debate</a>,&rdquo; as Tulane University geographer Richard Campanella would dub it, became a long-running public tussle over people&rsquo;s right to rebuild wherever they wanted, even if that meant they were putting themselves in harm&rsquo;s way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then-Mayor Ray Nagin had named Canizaro, a personal friend of then-President George W. Bush, to the panel he assembled to put together a plan for rebuilding New Orleans, where 110,000 homes and 20,000 businesses had flooded. Canizaro was a rich white Republican from the suburbs, equipped with Karl Rove&rsquo;s cell phone number, who had been either brave or foolish enough to volunteer to put together the redevelopment plan &mdash; a job that his fellow panel members were happy to have handed to him. And he had turned to me &mdash; then a reporter for The New York Times &ldquo;storm team&rdquo; who had a tourist&rsquo;s knowledge of New Orleans &mdash; to help him make up his mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I would demur on that day. But for 10 years, I&rsquo;ve been grappling with that question, first as a reporter for the Times and then as an author of <a href="http://books.simonandschuster.com/Katrina/Gary-Rivlin/9781451692228">a book about the rebuilding of New Orleans</a>. Coming up with the right answer is for me as difficult today as it was then.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those who argued in favor of shrinking usually began by citing census figures. The city&rsquo;s population had peaked at 627,525 people in 1960, but that was before the integration of the public schools and the white flight that saw 160,000 people leave the city over the next two decades. By the time of Katrina, New Orleans had an estimated 455,000 residents &mdash; and with maybe 100,000 left a few months after the storm, who knew, Canizaro and others were asking, if the population would get back to even 300,000?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;It doesn&rsquo;t take a genius to figure if you&rsquo;re missing 40 percent of your original population, then there&rsquo;s going to be shrinkage in the amount of land that&rsquo;s going to be needed,&rdquo; Canizaro said to me on New Year&rsquo;s Day, 2006, with his big decision barely a week away. And yet he confessed that he wasn&rsquo;t ready to declare a death sentence for any New Orleans neighborhood.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Geographers didn&rsquo;t seem to have any trouble reaching a similar consensus on the need to shrink the city&rsquo;s footprint. Craig Colton, who taught geography at LSU, heard from colleagues around the country in the weeks after Katrina. To them, the only question was whether 20 percent or 40 percent of the city&rsquo;s landmass should revert to wetlands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know exactly where I would draw the line, but I assume that&rsquo;s what the city is trying to figure out right now,&rdquo; Colton had told me a couple of months after the storm. Roughly half the city sat below sea level, Colton said, but that didn&rsquo;t mean he would decree half the city out of bounds. A community sitting a few feet below sea level might be deemed an &ldquo;intermediate zone,&rdquo; where people would be permitted to rebuild &mdash; if homes were jacked up high enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The city needs to choose some level below sea level and declare it economically unfeasible to build in areas that are at that elevation or lower,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="rivlin-nola-feature-nolahousing-map" src="https://espnfivethirtyeight.files.wordpress.com/2015/08/rivlin-nola-feature-nolahousing-map.png?w=610&amp;h=600" style="height:600px; width:610px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Colton&rsquo;s colleague Bruce Sharky, a professor of landscape architecture at LSU, specialized in land use issues. Sharky, too, said he thought it would be irresponsible to rebuild all of New Orleans. He started making regular trips to the city shortly after the floodwaters receded (accomplished in three weeks despite the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers&rsquo; estimate that it would take at least 80 days). He had seen the enormity of the disaster that had befallen New Orleans East, parts of which sat 7 feet below sea level, and Lakeview, a neighborhood on the west side of the city where the average home sat 3 feet below sea level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The government is going to spend, what, $100 billion or more to rebuild New Orleans &mdash; and for what?&rdquo; Sharky asked a few months after Katrina. &ldquo;If we don&rsquo;t do things differently, it can happen again next year.&rdquo;<a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-the-plan-to-shrink-new-orleans-after-katrina-failed/#fn-1">1</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Money was very much on Canizaro&rsquo;s mind in early 2006. He asked me to imagine the cost of providing police, fire protection, garbage pickup, and other city services to half-built neighborhoods in low-lying New Orleans. Every expert was telling him the same thing: The city couldn&rsquo;t afford to let every last neighborhood come back. Fewer people meant less tax revenue and therefore less money to spend on everything from police and fire to street repairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet by that point, Canizaro was admitting that it was inevitable that he would duck the tough call and not prohibit low-lying neighborhoods from rebuilding. He was a white man leading the redevelopment of a city that was two-thirds black. Of the 353,000 people living in a part of the city that flooded, 265,000 were black.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Unfortunately, a lot of poor African-Americans had everything they own destroyed here,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;So we have to be careful about dictating what&rsquo;s going to happen, especially me as a white man.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Race was a vital element of the Great Footprint Debate &mdash; and for me (also white), it turned a hard decision into an impossible one. For decades, racial covenants and discriminatory lending policies in the city meant black homeownership had been restricted to only a few neighborhoods. Barbara Major, the co-chairwoman of the mayoral panel on which Canizaro served, noted that there was a reason why so many black families lived in New Orleans East, as she did, and in other low-lying parts of the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Black people only moved there because all the high ground had been taken,&rdquo; said Major, who is black.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>John Logan, a sociology professor at Brown University, <a href="http://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/2005-06/05-068.html">broke down by race</a> (and other factors) the makeup of the blocks that Canizaro&rsquo;s experts wanted to leave uninhabited. They were talking about land that housed 80 percent of the city&rsquo;s black population.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What do you tell those residents, many of them longing to return home? &ldquo;Look, sorry, we know that was the only land where you could pursue the dream of homeownership, but you&rsquo;re going to have to find another place to live?&rdquo; New Orleans East was mostly swampland in the 1960s when developers started building in the area. By 2005, it was home to 96,000 people, or one-fifth of the city&rsquo;s population, and it was where much of the city&rsquo;s black middle and professional classes lived, along with a large portion of its black elites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;It would kill the black psyche if New Orleans East isn&rsquo;t rebuilt,&rdquo; said Tangeyon Wall, who, along with her husband, had bought a home in one of the area&rsquo;s middle-tier subdivisions in 1991.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were other issues, of course, starting with property rights. &ldquo;This is America&rdquo; was a popular refrain voiced by black and white residents alike during the debate over the city&rsquo;s future. If they had the money, people said, who was the government to tell them they couldn&rsquo;t rebuild?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The solution devised by Canizaro was borrowed from the outside planners in plentiful supply in New Orleans in those first months after Katrina: Arm communities with the same elevation data the government had been using when it considered turning large parts of the city into green space. Give them access to the same range of planners and demographers and geologists that were advising Canizaro. Each neighborhood would then have four months to submit a plan that proves its long-term viability.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But how do you define &ldquo;viability&rdquo;? Was it a commitment from 50 percent of a community&rsquo;s residents that they would rebuild? Seventy percent? The impracticality of making these choices helped doom the plan, which was immediately unpopular in the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nagin rejected the proposal because he was in the middle of a tough re-election campaign. His good friend David White, another suburban resident on the rebuilding panel, was among those telling Nagin that to embrace Canizaro&rsquo;s plan was to commit political suicide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I told him that from a planning standpoint, it probably made a lot of sense,&rdquo; White said. &ldquo;But from a human standpoint, it made no sense at all.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the end, no neighborhoods were declared off-limits. But driving around New Orleans these days, it&rsquo;s still not obvious that was the correct answer. Lakeview, a prosperous white community, looks better than it did before the storm. Some residents have elevated their houses, and the city is now better protected than it was pre-Katrina, after the federal government spent $14.5 billion to rebuild the levees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet those I spoke with estimate that New Orleans East is only about 80 percent back, and that the Seventh Ward, a black working-class neighborhood, is maybe 60 percent back.<a href="http://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-the-plan-to-shrink-new-orleans-after-katrina-failed/#fn-2">2</a> In the Lower Ninth Ward, where the average resident was living on $16,000 a year before the hurricane, the population is only 36 percent of what it was. In many of those neighborhoods, there are only a few houses on some blocks, raising the same questions about the long-term cost to the city of providing services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jeff Thomas, a lawyer who worked in a special unit run by the city&rsquo;s recovery czar in the first years after the flood, looks back on the Great Debate as a high-minded argument with no basis in reality. He sees the idea of seizing people&rsquo;s property as &ldquo;a nonstarter, constitutional law-wise, and also because of funding issues.&rdquo; Over coffee earlier this year, Thomas laid out the steps the city would have needed to take before bringing in the bulldozers and converting a neighborhood back to swampland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;You firstly have to justify the eminent domain of an entire community, &ldquo; Thomas said. &ldquo;If you don&rsquo;t have universal buy-in to be bought out, which here you wouldn&rsquo;t have, you then have to say why that neighborhood or that one. But in the context of New Orleans, you&rsquo;re going to be hard-pressed to demonstrate that one neighborhood in the bowl is less safe than another neighborhood in the bowl.&rdquo; (The bowl refers to the many sections of central New Orleans that are below sea level.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And if somehow the city got past that threshold? &ldquo;Then you have to individually buy out hundreds, if not thousands of properties in that community at fair market values,&rdquo; Thomas continued. By way of comparison, Thomas mentioned the 40 acres the city gave to the federal government so it would build a new Veterans Affairs hospital near the center of town rather than in the suburbs. &ldquo;That meant buying out approximately 160 buildings,&rdquo; said Thomas, who worked on that deal for a good portion of his time inside City Hall, &ldquo;and that costs $75 million.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those pushing the city to take bold action after Katrina, however, already had an answer to that. &ldquo;We need an FDR or someone like that who says, &lsquo;This is hard, but this is for the collective good,&rsquo;&rdquo; said Sharky, one of the LSU professors. &ldquo;You take that $100 billion and say here&rsquo;s how we&rsquo;re going to make a safer New Orleans, with better schools and better infrastructure.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Why The Plan To Shrink New Orleans Failed', 0, 0, NULL, 0, 6, 0);
